{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567375"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:00:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:00:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18967"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18967"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.48,0.09,0.18,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11701"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80552"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11701"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18967"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65843"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5711"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11409"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27528"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80552"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA palliative care physician is caring for a patient with terminal cancer who is experiencing severe pain. The physician increases the dose of opioid medication to control the pain, knowing this may potentially suppress respiratory function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical principle that supports this medical decision?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Principle of medical futility","Doctrine of double effect","Active euthanasia is acceptable if requested by the patient","Utilitarian ethical framework","Principle of patient autonomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edoctrine of double effect\u003C/strong\u003E is the ethical principle that justifies an action which may cause harm if the harm is unintended and the action is primarily aimed at achieving a good outcome. In this case, the physician\u0027s primary intention is to relieve pain, even though the medication may have the unintended consequence of respiratory depression.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive euthanasia is acceptable if requested by the patient\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes intentionally causing death, which is different from accepting a possible unintended outcome\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrinciple of medical futility\u003C/strong\u003E - This relates to withholding treatments that would not benefit the patient, not to providing symptom relief\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrinciple of patient autonomy\u003C/strong\u003E - While patient consent is important, this principle does not specifically address the ethical justification for accepting unintended harmful effects\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUtilitarian ethical framework\u003C/strong\u003E - While this considers outcomes, it does not specifically address the distinction between intended and unintended effects\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe doctrine of double effect requires four conditions: the action itself must be morally good, the good effect must not arise from the bad effect, the intention must be to achieve the good effect, and there must be proportionate reason for causing the harm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The doctrine of double effect states that an action which causes harm may be ethically permissible if the harm was not intended and is outweighed by the intended good effect.","In palliative care, providing pain relief that may shorten life is ethically justified if the primary intention is symptom control rather than hastening death.","The four conditions of double effect are: the action must be morally good, the good effect must not arise from the bad effect, the intention must be good, and there must be proportionate reason."],"references":["QUT. End of Life Law in Australia - Voluntary Assisted Dying. [online]. 2024. [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://end-of-life.qut.edu.au/assisteddying","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","Browne J, Dittborn M, Brierley J. The doctrine of double effect. Arch Dis Child Educ Pract Ed. 2021 Oct;106(5):304-305. doi: 10.1136/archdischild-2020-320615. Epub 2021 Jan 15. PMID: 33452012. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33452012/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65843"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18967"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65843"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T14:59:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T15:00:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11701"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80552"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioe